<protolog id="rid.286_nm.418" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.418" exemplar-doi="10.1601/ex.418" rank="species">Methanopyrus kandleri</organism><reference id="rid.286"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Kurr</surname><given-names>M.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Huber</surname><given-names>R.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>König</surname><given-names>H.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Jannasch</surname><given-names>H.W.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Fricke</surname><given-names>H.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Trincone</surname><given-names>A.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Kristjansson</surname><given-names>J.K.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Stetter</surname><given-names>K.O.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Methanopyrus kandleri, gen. and sp. nov. represents a novel group of hyperthermophilic methanogens, growing at 110 C.</article-title><year>1991</year><volume>156</volume><fpage>239</fpage><lpage>247</lpage><source id="118">Archives of Microbiology</source><abbrev>Arch Microbiol</abbrev><issn>0302-8933</issn><essn>1432-072X</essn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1007/BF00262992</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <i>Methanopyrus</i> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><i>Methanopyrus</i> (Me.tha.no.py'rus M.L.n. <i>methanum</i> methane; Gr. neutr, n. <i>pyr</i>. fire; M.L. masc. n. <i>Methanopyrus</i> the "methane fire" (the hyperthermophilic methanogen))</s></p><p class="description"><s>Gram-positive motile rods, occuring singly and in chains.</s><s>No spores formed.</s><s>Cell division by septa formation.</s><s>Double-layered cell envelope.</s><s>Sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS)-sensitive S-layer and SDS-resistant inner pseudomurein-sacculus.</s><s>Pseudomurein lacking N-acetylglucosamine and containing L-ornithine.</s><s>DNA-dependent RNA polymerase of the AB'B''C subunit pattern.</s><s>Cyclic 2,3-diphosphoglycerate present.</s><s>Core lipid consists of 2,3-di-O-phytanylglycerol.</s><s>Growth at 4% NaCl and up to 110°C.</s><s>No growth at 80°C or below.</s><s>Epifluorescence at 420 nm.</s><s>Methane is formed from H<sub>2</sub> +CO<sub>2</sub>.</s><s>DNA base composition 60 mol% GC.</s><s>By 16S rRNA sequence, no specific relation to any phylum of methanogens so far described.</s><s>Habitat: anaerobic hot sites within the Guaymas and Kolbeinsey submarine hydrothermal systems.</s></p><p class="description"><s>Type species: <i>Methanopyrus kandleri</i></s></p></content></protolog>